sentence: Stocks were struggling to hold onto modest gains in Tuesday trade following disappointing financial results earlier today by Dow component stock Wal-Mart ( WMT ), upstaging a rally for European stocks on expectations for additional economic stimulus.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average has flirted with a new record high several times today while the Nasdaq Composite index slipped into the red following a decline for chipmaker stocks.
Wall Street got a boost before the opening bell today, with U.S. housing starts rising to a 7-1/2 year high, climbing over 20% during April to a seasonally-adjusted rate of 1.135 million new homes.
Wall Street had been looking for a 11% gain and an annualized pace of 1.03 million homes.
Contractors pulled permits at a 1.14 million yearly clip, rising 10% over year-ago levels and beating estimates for a 1.07 million pace.
Retail earnings were in focus Tuesday, following financial results by Wal-Mart, TJX Companies ( TJX ) and Home Depot ( HD ).
TJX and HD both beat analyst estimates, but investors were spooked by Wal-Mart results, which suggested consumers still were not spending as much on consumables as they did last year.

EU-zone equity markets all rallied overnight in response to dovish comments from ECB members Benoit Coeure and Christian Noyer, both of whom endorsed more aggressive stimulus efforts to compensate for the recent surge in EU bond yields.
German bund yields fell while the DAX rallied by more than 2%, encouraging gains in U.S. markets before the open.
Crude oil was down $1.91 to $57.52 per barrel.
Natural gas was down 5 cents to $3.02 per 1 million BTU.
Gold was down $20.30 to $1,207.20 an ounce, while silver was down 66 cents to $17.07 an ounce.
Copper was down 7 cents to $2.83 per pound.
Among energy ETFs, the United States Oil Fund was down 3.43% to $19.74 with the United States Natural Gas Fund was down 1.88% to $14.62.
Amongst precious-metal funds, the Market Vectors Gold Miners ETF was unchanged at 21.56 while SPDR Gold Shares were down 1.37% to $115.91.
The iShares Silver Trust was down 3.43% to $16.31.

Here's where the U.S. markets stood at mid-day:

(-) YGE (-42.19%) Warns of "substantial doubt" that it can remain in business

(-) KRNY (-27.00%) Closed its stock offering and the related conversion from a mutual holding company to a stock holding company.
